               <head>Commentary on Rumi’s Masnavi</head>
               <msContents>
                  <summary>1 copy of Miftāḥ al-maʿānī by Hidāyat Allāh</summary>
                  <msItem class="http://lccn.loc.gov/sh2008112367 http://lccn.loc.gov/sh2006003807" n="1" xml:id="Uk_Delhi_Persian_1042-item1">
                     <author>
                        <persName xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" type="supplied" key="person_f7166">Hidāyat Allāh</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="per" type="supplied" key="person_f7166">هدايت الله </persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" key="work_22196">Miftāḥ al-maʿānī</title>
                     <title xml:lang="per" key="work_22196">مفتاح المعانى</title>
                     <textLang mainLang="per" otherLangs="ara">Persian and Arabic</textLang>
                     <note>
                        <p>Commentary on the <title>Mas̲navī-'i maʿnavī</title>of <persName key="person_98930150" role="ant">Jalāl al-Dīn Rūmī</persName> (d. 670/1271) by <persName key="person_f7166" role="aut">Hidāyat Allāh</persName> compiled from the research transmitted by his master, <persName key="person_f7522" role="ant">Sayyid ʿAbd al-Fattāḥ al-ʿAskarī al-Ḥusaynī al-Dihlavī</persName>, completed according to Levy circa 1049/1639-40 based on the authority of <persName key="person_68918448" role="cataloguer">Aloys Sprenger</persName>’s Oudh Catalogue (p. 492). 
                        </p>
                        <p>Dated colophon to book 5 (f. 254v): completed at <placeName>Shāhjahānābād</placeName>, 10 Ramaz̤ān in RY 42 of <persName key="person_6178410" role="oth">Emperor ʿĀlamgīr I</persName>, (1111)/1 March 1700. 
                        </p>
                        <p>Dated colophon to book 6 defective (f. 316v): completed Friday, 4 Z̲[ī] al-Ḥijjah 11[0]3 (figures written in reverse order)/17 August 1692. </p>
                        <p>Tight scribal nastaʿlīq and shikastah āmīz. 
Annotations and corrections in margins. 
</p>
                        <p>Stamped foliation. 
</p>
                        <p>Lacking original binding.
Binding damaged, spine intact (tooled reddish brown leather exterior embellished with medallions and outer bands of oxidised silver); doublures reddish leather. </p>
                        <p>Folios bound, but detached from covers; cropped, wormholes, later repairs. 
</p>
                        <p>Condition fragile. 
</p>
                     </note>
